13
00:00:56,740 --> 00:01:01,160
Now, watch and compare what happens when you pronounce these vowels:

14
00:01:08,080 --> 00:01:12,000
Do you see a difference in how your tongue and jaw move?

15
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:14,840
When you pronounce the /ɑ/ sound,

16
00:01:14,840 --> 00:01:18,180
your tongue and jaw move into one position only.

17
00:01:18,180 --> 00:01:20,876
So you pronounce just one sound.

18
00:01:20,880 --> 00:01:24,720
That's why the /ɑ/ is called a "monophthong,"

19
00:01:24,720 --> 00:01:27,900
which means "a single sound."

20
00:01:27,900 --> 00:01:32,160
However, when you pronounce the /aʊ/ vowel,

21
00:01:32,160 --> 00:01:36,760
your tongue and jaw move from one position to another.

22
00:01:36,760 --> 00:01:39,800
The /aʊ/ is called a "diphthong,"

23
00:01:39,800 --> 00:01:44,800
which means that it's made by merging two single sounds into one.

24
00:01:47,840 --> 00:01:51,080
That's why your jaw and tongue change their positions

25
00:01:51,080 --> 00:01:52,780
as you make the first sound .

26
00:01:52,800 --> 00:01:55,000
and then connect it to the second

27
00:01:59,160 --> 00:02:02,040
There are three diphthongs in American English,

28
00:02:02,080 --> 00:02:06,160
the /aʊ/, the /ɔɪ/ and the /aɪ/,

29
00:02:07,540 --> 00:02:14,080
as in the  words "bow," "boy," and "by."

30
00:02:14,120 --> 00:02:18,760
We'll cover the /ɔɪ/ and the /aɪ/ in our other videos.

31
00:02:18,860 --> 00:02:23,040
As for the /aʊ/, let's find out how to pronounce this sound.

32
00:02:25,420 --> 00:02:28,000
To make the /aʊ/ diphthong correctly,

33
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:30,040
you need to pronounce two sounds

34
00:02:30,040 --> 00:02:33,100
and make a smooth connection between them.

35
00:02:33,440 --> 00:02:35,540
This is how you do that.

36
00:02:35,540 --> 00:02:39,480
Start with making the /ɑ/ sound.

37
00:02:39,480 --> 00:02:42,880
Open your mouth as wide as possible.

38
00:02:42,880 --> 00:02:47,680
Relax your lips and allow them to rest in a neutral position.

39
00:02:51,080 --> 00:02:52,960
Flatten your tongue

40
00:02:54,440 --> 00:02:57,220
and place it very low in your mouth.

41
00:02:59,980 --> 00:03:04,820
The tip of your tongue should be touching the back of your bottom front teeth.

42
00:03:06,420 --> 00:03:12,340
Next, connect the /ɑ/ to the /ʊ/ sound.

43
00:03:12,340 --> 00:03:15,420
Smoothly move your jaw up,

44
00:03:15,420 --> 00:03:18,680
until your mouth is almost closed.

45
00:03:18,680 --> 00:03:22,460
Then pull the back of your tongue to your throat.

46
00:03:26,140 --> 00:03:30,560
The first sound in a diphthong is typically longer and louder.

47
00:03:30,640 --> 00:03:35,780
So, make sure that you pronounce a nice and full /ɑ/

48
00:03:35,780 --> 00:03:38,580
and then connect it to the /ʊ/.

49
